Git Command Cheat Sheet

    Clone Repository (if you haven't already):

    bash

git clone <repository-url>

Navigate to Your Repository:

bash

cd <repository-name>

Fetch All Branches (to ensure you have the latest list of branches):

bash

git fetch --all

Switch to the main Branch:

bash

git checkout main

Pull Latest Changes from main:

bash

git pull origin main

Create and Switch to a New Branch (replace <new-branch-name> with your branch name):

bash

git checkout -b <new-branch-name>

Make Your Changes:

    Edit, add, or delete files as needed in your project.

Add Changes to Stage:

bash

git add .

Commit Your Changes:

bash

git commit -m "Your commit message"

Push Your Branch to Remote:

bash

git push -u origin <new-branch-name>

Create Pull Request:

    For CLI: You need to use a tool like Hub or GitHub CLI.
        With GitHub CLI, for example:

        bash

        gh pr create --base main --head <new-branch-name> --title "Your PR title" --body "Description of changes"

    Alternatively, you can create a pull request via your repository's website on GitHub/GitLab/Bitbucket.

Submit Pull Request:

    Finalize and submit the pull request through the web interface or CLI tool.
